---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About"
	description="Who I am and why I write this."
	pubDate={new Date('Jun 12 2026')}
>
	<p>
		I'm Jeff Huang. I was on the founding team of <a href="https://genkit.dev">Genkit</a>,
		Google's open-source SDK for building and deploying agent harnesses, and I lead Genkit
		Python. Before that I worked on Firebase's serverless platform — Cloud Functions and
		Extensions — spending years on the same core problem: take infrastructure that's
		genuinely hard, hide the parts developers shouldn't have to care about, make the happy
		path nearly effortless, and leave fine-grained hooks for everyone who needs to go
		deeper.
	</p>
	<p>
		Agent infrastructure is that problem again. Interrupts and resumption, tool approval,
		fallbacks, session state, middleware — most teams are hand-rolling all of it, the way
		everyone hand-rolled deployment scripts before serverless. I spend my days inside that
		boundary: designing the hooks, porting them across languages, watching what real users
		do with them.
	</p>
	<p>
		Most posts here follow the same arc: read an open-source harness — Claude Code, Goose,
		Open SWE, or the internal agents that companies like Stripe, Ramp, and Coinbase
		describe on their engineering blogs — pull out a pattern they've converged on, distill
		it into a best practice, and show how to build it with Genkit. It's reading I'd be
		doing anyway; this is just the version with the notes written down.
	</p>
	<p>
		Two rules: code snippets come from real, committed code, and numbers come from runs that
		actually happened.
	</p>
	<p>
		Find me on <a href="https://github.com/jeffdh5">GitHub</a>. Source for this site is
		<a href="https://github.com/jeffdh5/agent-eng-blog">here</a>.
	</p>
</Layout>
